JPA vs Hibernate — what exactly is each one?
JPA (Jakarta Persistence API) is just a specification — 
                a set of Java interfaces, annotations (@Entity, @Id, @OneToMany...),
                and rules written in a document. 
                It ships no executable code.
                It defines what an ORM must do, not how.
Hibernate is the implementation — 
    it reads your @Entity classes,
    maintains an in-memory cache of managed objects (the "persistence context"), 
    generates SQL, executes it via JDBC, and maps result sets back to objects. 
    When Spring Boot starts, it wires Hibernate as the JPA provider automatically.
Spring Data JPA sits on top of both.
    It reads your JpaRepository interface at startup, 
    generates proxy classes that implement it,
    and delegates every call down to Hibernate. 
    You never write a single line of SQL for basic CRUD.
The relationship in one sentence: JPA is the contract, Hibernate is the worker, Spring Data JPA is the manager that assigns the work.

